# Azure Data Processing Lab

In this lab we will create a data workflow that will continuously pull news stories from the web, transform them on the fly into a useable format, and then analyze their topics using the Microsoft Cognitive Services available through the data lake analytics service. At the end we will visualize these story topics in Power BI. We will use a storage account, logic apps, stream analytics, data lake analytics (U-SQL) and finally Power BI. At the end, all these services can be deleted. The entire project could schematically drawn out as such:

 

Our first step is to create somewhere to store the data….

 
# Exercise 1: Create a storage account

1. In the Portal search for &quot;storage accounts&quot; (not &quot;classic&quot;)
2. Click &quot;add&quot; to create a new storage account
3. Give it a globally unique name
4. Leave the Deployment model as &quot;Resource manager&quot;, the Account kind as &quot;General purpose&quot; and the Performance as &quot;Standard&quot;.
5. Select &quot;Locally-redundant&quot; storage (cheaper)
6. And create a new resource group called &quot;datademo&quot; in which we will put all the items we create in this workshop.
7. Pick a location near you.
8. Click &quot;Create&quot;.

##Task 4: Extract Key Phrases from the news feed files with a U-SQL query
### 1 Using the Azure Portal

1. In the portal, open the Data Lake Analytics
2. Click on &quot;New Job&quot; in the left-hand blade
3. Fill in the &quot;Job Name&quot;
4. Select between 5 and 30 AUs (degrees of parallelism). The more, the faster the job will run.
5. Then paste or type the following code into the code window. (Note: it&#39;s case sensitive!):

REFERENCEASSEMBLY [TextCommon];

REFERENCEASSEMBLY [TextKeyPhrase];

@titles =

    EXTRACT title string,

            pubdate string,

            date string,

            hour string,

            fileName string

    FROM&quot;wasb://processednewsfeed@&lt;YOUR STORAGE ACCOUNT NAME HERE&gt;.blob.core.windows.net/{date}{\*}/{hour}{\*}/{fileName}{\*}.csv&quot;

    USING Extractors.Tsv();

//the KeyPhraseExtractor requires a field named &quot;Text&quot;, which is the field it will process

@titlesforextractor =

    SELECT title AS Text

    FROM@titles;

@keyphrases =

    PROCESS@titlesforextractor

    PRODUCE Text,

            KeyPhrase string

    READONLY Text

    USINGnew Cognition.Text.KeyPhraseExtractor();

@keyphrasecounts =

    SELECT T.KeyPhrase,

           COUNT( \* ) AS KeyPhraseCount

    FROM@keyphrases

       CROSSAPPLY

            new Cognition.Text.Splitter(&quot;KeyPhrase&quot;) AS T(KeyPhrase)

    GROUPBY T.KeyPhrase;

OUTPUT@keyphrasecounts

TO&quot;wasb://processednewsfeed@&lt;YOUR STORAGE ACCOUNT NAME HERE&gt;.blob.core.windows.net/KeyPhraseCounts.csv&quot;

ORDERBY KeyPhraseCount DESC

USING Outputters.Tsv();

1. Click &quot;Submit Job&quot;, sit back, and relax.
2. When the job is done, the output file will appear in your blob storage at the root of the &quot;processednewsfeed&quot; container.
